# TypeScript Standards

## Strict Mode

- All code must pass `strict: true`
- No `any` — use `unknown` and narrow types
- Explicit return types for exported functions

## Error Handling

```typescript
// ❌ BAD: Silent catch
try {
  await fetchData()
} catch (e) {}

// ✅ GOOD: Handle or rethrow
try {
  await fetchData()
} catch (error) {
  console.error('Failed to fetch:', error)
  throw new Error('Data fetch failed', { cause: error })
}
```

## Type Definitions

```typescript
// ❌ BAD: Inline types repeated
function process(data: { id: string; name: string }) {}

// ✅ GOOD: Named types in types/
import type { ProcessData } from '@/types'
function process(data: ProcessData) {}
```

## Async Functions

```typescript
// ❌ BAD: Unhandled promise
async function load() {
  fetchData() // Missing await
}

// ✅ GOOD: Always await or handle
async function load() {
  await fetchData()
}
```

## Null Checks

```typescript
// ❌ BAD: Non-null assertion
const value = maybeNull!.property

// ✅ GOOD: Explicit check
if (maybeNull) {
  const value = maybeNull.property
}
```

## Imports

- Use `type` imports for types: `import type { Foo } from './types'`
- Use path alias: `@/` instead of relative `../../../`
